Note the [[aspiration (phonetics)|aspiration]] contrast and the lack of [[voice (phonetics)|voicing]] contrast for [[stop consonant|stops]]. The [[affricate consonant|affricates]] are grouped with the stops for compactness in  the chart.

#Some linguists prefer to analyze {{IPA|/j/}} and {{IPA|/w/}} as part of [[final (linguistics)|finals]] to make them analogous to the {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} [[Syllable medial|medial]]s in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]], especially in comparative phonological studies. However, since final-heads only appear with [[initial (linguistics)|null initial]], {{IPA|/k/}} or {{IPA|/kʰ/}}, analyzing them as part of the initials greatly reduces the count of finals at the cost of adding only four initials. 
#Some linguists analyze a {{IPA|/ʔ/}} ([[glottal stop]]) in place of the null initial when a [[vowel]] begins a sound.
#In casual speech, many native speakers do not distinguish between {{IPA|/n/}} and {{IPA|/l/}}, nor between {{IPA|/ŋ/}} and the null initial.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Yip|Matthews|2001|pp=3–4}}</ref> Usually they pronounce only {{IPA|/l/}} and the null initial. See the discussion on [[Cantonese phonology#Historical change|phonological shift]] below.

The position of the [[coronal consonant|coronals]] varies from [[dental consonant|dental]] to [[alveolar consonant|alveolar]], with {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/tʰ/}} more likely to be dental. The position of the coronal [[affricate consonant|affricates]] and [[sibilant consonant|sibilants]] {{IPA|/t͡s/}}, {{IPA|/t͡sʰ/}}, {{IPA|/s/}} is alveolar and articulatory findings indicate they are not significantly palatalized by vowels.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Zee |first=Eric |date=1996 |title=Phonological Changes in Hong Kong Cantonese |journal=Current Issues In Language and Society |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=192-198 |doi=10.1080/13520529609615469}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Lee |first=W.-S. |last2=Zee |first2=E. |date=2010 |title=Articulatory characteristics of the coronal stop, affricate, and fricative in cantonese |url=http://www.cuhk.edu.hk/journal/jcl/jcl/chin_lin/38/38_2_6.html |journal=Journal of Chinese Linguistics |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=336-372 |doi=}}</ref> Historically, there was another series of alveolo-palatal sibilants as discussed [[Cantonese phonology#Historical change|below]].

===Vowels and terminals===
{{multiple image  | align = right  | direction = vertical  | image1 = Cantonese vowel chart.svg | width1 = 250 | caption1  = Chart of monophthongs used in Cantonese, from {{Harvcoltxt|Zee|1999|p=59}}| image2  = Cantonese diphthong chart.svg | width2 = 250 | caption2  = Chart of diphthongs used in Cantonese, from {{Harvcoltxt|Zee|1999|p=59}}}}

[[Final (linguistics)|Finals]] (or rimes) are the part of the sound after the initial. A final is typically composed of a main vowel ([[Nucleus (syllable)|nucleus]]) and a terminal ([[syllable coda|coda]]).

A main vowel can be long or short, depending on [[vowel length]]. The vowels {{IPA|/aː, ɐ/}}, {{IPA|/ɛː, e/}} and {{IPA|/ɔː, o/}} are each long-short pairs with corresponding [[formant]]s on acoustic findings,<ref>{{citation | last= Zee | first=Eric | year=2003 | title=Frequency Analysis of the Vowels in Cantonese from 50 Male and 50 Female Speakers | journal=Proceedings of the 15th International Congress of Phonetic Sciences | volume= | issue= | pages=1117–1120 |url= https://www.internationalphoneticassociation.org/icphs-proceedings/ICPhS2003/papers/p15_1117.pdf |bibcode = }}</ref><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Bauer|Benedict|1997|pp=46–47}}</ref> while the vowels {{IPA|/œː, ɵ/}} are also phonologically analysed as a long-short pair. The vowels of Cantonese are as shown:

