A terminal can be a [[semivowel]], a [[nasal consonant]], or a [[stop consonant]]. The semivowel {{IPA|/i/}} is rounded after rounded vowels.<ref name="Diphthong">{{citation | author=Zee, Eric | year=1999 | title=An acoustical analysis of the diphthongs in Cantonese | journal=Proceedings of the 14th International Congress of Phonetic Sciences | volume= | issue= | pages=1101–1105 |url= https://www.internationalphoneticassociation.org/icphs-proceedings/ICPhS1999/papers/p14_1101.pdf |bibcode = }}</ref> Nasal consonants can occur as base syllables in their own right and these are known as syllabic nasals. The stop consonants ({{IPA|/p, t, k/}}) are [[No audible release|unreleased]] ({{IPA|[p̚, t̚, k̚]}}).

