#Finals {{IPA|/ɛːu/}},<ref name="Diphthong"/> {{IPA|/ɛːm/}}, {{IPA|/ɛːn/}}, {{IPA|/ɛːp/}}, {{IPA|/ɛːt/}} and {{IPA|/œːt/}}<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Bauer|Benedict|1997|pp=78–79}}</ref> only appear in colloquial pronunciations of characters.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Bauer|Benedict|1997|pp=60}}</ref> They are absent from some analyses and romanization systems.

A narrow transcription of the vowels that are conventionally transcribed {{IPA|/aː, ɐ/}} is actually {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɐː}}, {{IPA link|ɜ}}]}}, as both are central and not fully open. The same can be said of the diphthongs {{IPA|/aːi, aːu, ɐi, ɐu/}}, as their actual phonetic realizations are {{IPA|[ɐːi, ɐːu, ɜi, ɜu]}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Zee|1999|p=59}}</ref> See the vowel charts at the right.

When the three [[checked tone]]s are separated, the stop codas {{IPA|/p, t, k/}} become [[allophone]]s of the nasal codas {{IPA|/m, n, ŋ/}} respectively, because they are in the [[complementary distribution]] in which the former three appear in the checked tones and the latter three appear in the non-checked tones.

==Tones==
[[File:Cantonese tones.svg|thumb|right|Relative fundamental-frequency contours for six Cantonese tones with examples and Jyutping/Yale tone numbers (modified from {{Harvcoltxt|Francis|2008}})]]
Like other Chinese dialects, Cantonese uses [[tone contour]]s to distinguish words, with the number of possible tones depending on the type of final. While Guangzhou Cantonese generally distinguishes between high-falling and high level tones, the two have merged in Hong Kong Cantonese and Macau Cantonese, yielding a system of six different tones in syllables ending in a semi-vowel or [[nasal stop|nasal consonant]]. (Some of these have more than one realization, but such differences are not used to distinguish words.) In finals that end in a [[stop consonant]], the number of tones is reduced to three; in Chinese descriptions, these "[[checked tone]]s" are treated separately by [[Historical linguistics|diachronic]] convention, so that Cantonese is traditionally said to have nine tones. However, phonetically these are a conflation of tone and final consonant; the number of phonemic tones is six in Hong Kong and seven in Guangzhou.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Bauer|Benedict|1997|pp=119–120}}</ref>

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
!Syllable type!!colspan=6|Open syllables!!colspan=3|Checked syllables
|-
