{{other uses}}
{{wikt|embarrassment of riches}}

An '''embarrassment of riches''' is an [[idiom]] that means an [[:wikt:overabundance|overabundance]] of something, or too much of a good thing, that originated in 1738 as [[John Ozell]]'s translation of a French play, ''[[L'Embarras des richesses]]'' (1726), by [[Léonor Jean Christine Soulas d'Allainval]].

Example: "All four of them have their own cars but there's no room in the driveway&mdash;an embarrassment of riches".

The idiom has also inspired other works and been included in their titles. This includes: ''The Embarrassment of Riches'' (1906), a play by [[Louis K. Anspacher]],<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0030682/otherworks Louis K. Anspacher, other works at the Imdb]</ref> and a 1918 [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] of the same name based on the Anspacher play;
a [[Embarrassment of Riches (EP)|2006 music album of this name]] by [[Elephant Micah]]; the history book ''[[The Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the Golden Age]]'' by [[Simon Schama]]; and ''[[An Embarrassment of Riches]]'', a 2000 novel written by Filipino author [[Charlson Ong]].

