{{India-writer-stub}}

{{refimprove|date=March 2016}} [[Vedic Sanskrit]] is the [[Indo-Aryan language]] used in the religious hymns known as the [[Vedas]], composed from the early-to-mid 2nd millennium through to the mid 1st millennium, BCE. It was a spoken language during that period. Its grammar differs in certain respects from the grammar of the later Classical [[Sanskrit]].
==Grammar== [[File:ANCIENT_SANSKRIT_ON_HEMP_BASED_PAPER._HEMP_WAS_A_COMMON_AND_DURABLE_FIBRE_IN_THE_PRODUCTION_OF_%22RAG%22_PAPER_FROM_200_BCE_TO_THE_1850_AD.jpg|right|thumb|Ancient Sanskrit on hemp-based paper. Hemp fiber was commonly used in the production of paper from 200 BCE to the late 1800s.]] Compared with [[Sanskrit|Classical Sanskrit]], [[Vedic]] had a [[subjunctive mood]] absent in [[Pāṇini]]'s grammar and generally believed to have disappeared by then at least in common sentence constructions. All tenses could be conjugated in the subjunctive and [[optative mood]]s, in contrast to Classical Sanskrit, with no subjunctive and only a present optative. However, the old first-person subjunctive forms were used to complete the Classical Sanskrit imperative. The three [[Synthetic language|synthetic]] past tenses ([[imperfect]], [[perfect (grammar)|perfect]] and [[aorist]]) were still clearly distinguished semantically in (at least the earliest) Vedic. A fifth mood, the [[Injunctive mood|injunctive]], also existed.
Long-''i'' stems differentiate the [[Devi and Vrkis feminines]], a difference lost in Classical Sanskrit.
*The [[subjunctive mood]] of Vedic was also lost in Classical Sanskrit. Also, there was no fixed rule about the use of various tenses {{transl|sa|(''luṇ, laṇ'' and ''liṭ'')}}. *There were more than 12 ways of forming [[infinitive]]s in Vedic, of which Classical Sanskrit retained only one form. *Nominal declinations and verbal conjugation also changed pronunciation, although the spelling was mostly retained in Classical Sanskrit. E.g., along with the Classical Sanskrit's declension of ''deva-'' as {{transl|sa|''devaḥ''—''devau''—''devāḥ''}}, Vedic additionally allowed the forms {{transl|sa|''daivaḥ''—''daivā''—''daivāsaḥ''}}. Similarly Vedic has declined forms such as ''asmai'', ''tvai'', {{transl|sa|''yuṣmai''}}, ''tvā'', etc. for the first and second person pronouns, not found in Classical Sanskrit. The obvious reason is the attempt of Classical Sanskrit to regularize and standardize its grammar, which simultaneously led to a purge of older [[Proto-Indo-European language#Verb|Proto-Indo-European forms]]. *To emphasize that Proto-Indo-European and its immediate daughters were essentially end-inflected languages, both Proto-Indo-European and Vedic had independent prefix-morphemes. Such prefixes (especially for verbs) could come anywhere in the sentence, but in Classical Sanskrit, it became mandatory to attach them immediately before the verb.
==Morphology==
===Nouns=== Vedic is a highly [[inflection|inflected]] language with three [[grammatical gender]]s (masculine, feminine, neuter) and three numbers (singular, plural, [[dual grammatical number|dual]]). It has eight [[Grammatical case|cases]]: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Vocative case|vocative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], [[Instrumental case|instrumental]], [[Dative case|dative]], [[Ablative case|ablative]], [[Genitive case|genitive]], and [[Locative case|locative]].
In this article nouns are divided into five declensions. The declension which a noun belongs to is determined largely by form.
====The basic declension suffix scheme for nouns and adjectives==== The basic scheme is given in the table below — valid for almost all nouns and adjectives. However, according to the gender and the ending consonant/vowel of the uninflected word-stem, there are predetermined rules of compulsory ''sandhi'' which would then give the final inflected word.<ref>{{cite book |last1=MacDonell |first1=Arthur Anthony |title=A Vedic Grammar for Students |date=1916 |publisher=The Clarendon Press |location=Oxford |page=48}}</ref>
{|class="wikitable" ! !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural |- | '''Nominative''' | -ḥ (-Ø) || -āu (-ī) || -aḥ (-i) |- | '''Vocative''' | -Ø || -āu (-ī) || -aḥ (-i) |- | '''Accusative''' | -m (-Ø) || -āu (-ī) || -aḥ (-i) |- | '''Instrumental''' | -ā || -bhyām || -bhiḥ |- | '''Dative''' | -ai || -bhyām || -bhyaḥ |- | '''Ablative''' | -aḥ || -bhyām || -bhyaḥ |- | '''Genitive''' | -aḥ || -auḥ || -ām |- | '''Locative''' | -i || -auḥ || -su |}
====a-stems==== A-stems ({{IPA|[a]}} and {{IPA|[ɑː]}}) (also known as thematic stems) comprise the largest class of nouns. As a rule, nouns belonging to this class, with the uninflected stem ending in short-a ({{IPA|[a]}}), are either masculine or neuter. Nouns ending in long-ā ({{IPA|[ɑː]}}) are almost always feminine. A-stem adjectives take the masculine and neuter in short-a ({{IPA|[a]}}), and feminine in long-ā ({{IPA|[ɑː]}}) in their stems. This class is so big because it also comprises the Proto-Indo-European o-stems.
{| class="wikitable" |- !rowspan="2"| !colspan="3"| Masculine (''vīrá'' 'man, hero') !colspan="3"| Neuter (''havyá'' 'sacrificial oblation') !colspan="3"| Feminine (''íḷā'' 'refreshing draught, libation') |- ! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural |- | '''Nominative''' | vīráḥ || vīrā́ú || vīrā́ḥ (°ā́saḥ) || havyám || havyáu || havyā́, havyā́ni || íḷā || íḷai || ílāḥ |- | '''Vocative''' | vī́ra! || vī́rā́u! || vī́rāḥ (°āsaḥ)! || hávya! || hávyai! || hávyā! hávyāni! || íḷai! || íḷai! || ílāḥ! |- | '''Accusative''' | vīrám || vīrā́ú || vīrā́n || havyám || havyái || havyā́, havyā́ni || íḷām || íḷai || ílāḥ |- | '''Instrumental''' | vīráiṇa, vīrā́ || vīrā́bhyām || vīrāíḥ, vīráibhiḥ || havyáina, havyā́ || havyā́bhyām || havyāíḥ, havyáibhiḥ || íḷā, íḷayā || íḷābhyām || íḷābhiḥ |- | '''Dative''' | vīrā́ya || vīrā́bhyām || vīráibhyaḥ || havyā́ya || havyā́bhyām || havyáibhyaḥ || íḷāyai || íḷābhyām || íḷābhyaḥ |- | '''Ablative''' | vīrā́t || vīrā́bhyām || vīráibhyaḥ || havyā́t || havyā́bhyām || havyáibhyaḥ || íḷāyāḥ || íḷābhyām || íḷābhyaḥ |- | '''Genitive''' | vīrásya || vīráyauḥ || vīrā́ṇām || havyásya || havyáyauḥ || havyā́nām || íḷāyāḥ || íḷayauḥ || íḷānām |- | '''Locative''' | vīrái || vīráyauḥ || vīráiṣu || havyái || havyáyauḥ || havyáiṣu || íḷāyām || íḷayauḥ || íḷāsu |}
====i- and u-stems==== {| class="wikitable" |+ i-stems |- !rowspan="2"| !colspan="3"| Masc. (''pati'' 'host, husband') !colspan="3"| Neuter (''vāri'' 'water') !colspan="3"| Fem. (''mati'' 'thought') |- ! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural |- | '''Nominative''' | patis || patī || patayas || vāri || {{transl|sa|vāriṇī}} || {{transl|sa|vārīṇi}} || matis || matī || matayas |- | '''Vocative''' | patai! || patī! || patayas! || vāri, vārai! || {{transl|sa|vāriṇī}}! || {{transl|sa|vārīṇi}}! || matai! || matī! || matayas! |- | '''Accusative''' | patim || patī || patīn || vāri || {{transl|sa|vāriṇī}} || {{transl|sa|vārīṇi}} || matim || matī || matīs |- | '''Instrumental''' | patinā || patibhyām || patibhis || {{transl|sa|vāriṇā}} || vāribhyām || vāribhis || matyā || matibhyām || matibhis |- | '''Dative''' | patayai || patibhyām || patibhyas || {{transl|sa|vāriṇai}} || vāribhyām || vāribhyas || matyāi || matibhyām || matibhyas |- | '''Ablative''' | patais || patibhyām || patibhyas || {{transl|sa|vāriṇas}} || vāribhyām || vāribhyas || matyās || matibhyām || matibhyas |- | '''Genitive''' | patais || patyaus || patīnām || {{transl|sa|vāriṇas}} || {{transl|sa|vāriṇaus}} || {{transl|sa|vāriṇām}} || matyās || matyaus || matīnām |- | '''Locative''' | patāu || patyaus || {{transl|sa|patiṣu}} || {{transl|sa|vāriṇi}} || {{transl|sa|vāriṇaus}} || {{transl|sa|vāriṣu}} || matyām || matyaus || {{transl|sa|matiṣu}} |}
{| class="wikitable" |+ u-stems |- !rowspan="2"| !colspan="3"| Masc. (''vāyu'' 'wind') !colspan="3"| Neuter (''madhu'' 'honey') !colspan="3"| Fem. (''śatru'' 'she-enemy') |- ! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural |- | '''Nominative''' | vāyus || vāyū || vāyavas || madhu || madhunī || madhūni || śatrus || śatrū || śatravas |- | '''Vocative''' | vāyau! || vāyū! || vāyavas! || madhu! || madhunī! || madhūni! || śatrau! || śatrū! || śatravas! |- | '''Accusative''' | vāyum || vāyū || vāyūn || madhu || madhunī || madhūni || śatrum || śatrū || śatrūs |- | '''Instrumental''' | {{transl|sa|vāyuṇā}} || vāyubhyām || vāyubhis || madhunā || madhubhyām || madhubhis || śatrvā || śatrubhyām || śatrubhis |- | '''Dative''' | vāyavai || vāyubhyām || vāyubhyas || madhunai || madhubhyām || madhubhyas || śatrvāi || śatrubhyām || śatrubhyas |- | '''Ablative''' | vāyaus || vāyubhyām || vāyubhyas || madhunas || madhubhyām || madhubhyas || śatrvās || śatrubhyām || śatrubhyas |- | '''Genitive''' | vāyaus || vāyvaus || vāyūnām || madhunas || madhunaus || madhūnām || śatrvās || śatrvaus || {{transl|sa|śatrūṇām}} |- | '''Locative''' | vāyāu || vāyvaus || {{transl|sa|vāyuṣu}} || madhuni || madhunaus || {{transl|sa|madhuṣu}} || śatrvām || śatrvaus || {{transl|sa|śatruṣu}} |}
====ī- and ū -stems==== {{see also|Devi and Vrkis feminines}} Ī- and ū -stems are only feminine. {| class="wikitable" |- !rowspan="2"| !colspan="3"| {{transl|sa|ī}}-stems (''patnī'' 'hostess, wife') !colspan="3"| {{transl|sa|ū}}-stems (''vadhū'' 'bride') |- ! Singular !! Dual !! Plural ! Singular !! Dual !! Plural |- | '''Nominative''' | patnī || patnyāu || patnyas | vadhūs || vadhvāu || vadhvas |- | '''Vocative''' | patni! || patnyāu! || patnyas! | vadhu! || vadhvāu! || vadhvas! |- | '''Accusative''' | patnīm || patnyāu || patnīs | vadhūm || vadhvāu || vadhūs |- | '''Instrumental''' | patnyā || patnībhyām || patnībhis | vadhvā || vadhūbhyām || vadhūbhis |- | '''Dative''' | patnyāi || patnībhyām || patnībhyas | vadhvāi || vadhūbhyām || vadhūbhyas |- | '''Ablative''' | patnyās || patnībhyām || patnībhyas | vadhvās || vadhūbhyām || vadhūbhyas |- | '''Genitive''' | patnyās || patnyaus || patnīnām | vadhvās || vadhvaus || vadhūnām |- | '''Locative''' | patnyām || patnyaus || {{transl|sa|patnīṣu}} | vadhvām || vadhvaus || {{transl|sa|vadhūṣu}} |}
===={{transl|sa|ṛ}} and {{transl|sa|ṝ}}-stems==== {{transl|sa|ṛ}}-stems are predominantly [[Agent (grammar)|agental]] derivatives like neut. ''{{transl|sa|dātṛ}}'' 'giver', though also include kinship terms like masc. ''{{transl|sa|pitṛ}}'' 'father', ''{{transl|sa|naptṛ}}'' 'nephew', ''{{transl|sa|bhrātṛ}}" 'brother' and fem. ''{{transl|sa|mātṝ}}'' 'mother', ''{{transl|sa|duhitṝ}}'' 'daughter' and ''{{transl|sa|svasṝ}}'' 'sister'. {| class="wikitable" |- !rowspan="2"| !colspan="3"| Masculine (''{{transl|sa|pitṛ}}'' 'father') !colspan="3"| Neuter (''{{transl|sa|dātṛ}}'' 'giver') !colspan="3"| Feminine (''{{transl|sa|mātṝ}}'' 'mother') |- ! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural !! Singular !! Dual !! Plural |- | '''Nominative''' | pita || pitarāu || pitaras || {{transl|sa|dātṛ}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇī}} || {{transl|sa|dātṝṇi}} || mātā || mātārāu || mātāras |- | '''Vocative''' | pítar! || pitarāu! || pitaras! || {{transl|sa|dātṛ}}! || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇī}}! || {{transl|sa|dātṝṇi}}! || mātār! || mātārāu! || mātāras! |- | '''Accusative''' | pitaram || pitarāu || {{transl|sa|pitṝn}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛ}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇī}} || {{transl|sa|dātṝṇi}} || mātāram || mātārāu || {{transl|sa|mātṝs}} |- | '''Instrumental''' | pitrā || {{transl|sa|pitṛbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|pitṛbhis}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇā}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛbhis}} || mātārā || {{transl|sa|mātṝbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|mātṝbhis}} |- | '''Dative''' | pitrai || {{transl|sa|pitṛbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|pitṛbhyas}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇai}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛbhyas}} || mātārai || {{transl|sa|mātṝbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|mātṝbhyas}} |- | '''Ablative''' | pitur, pitras || {{transl|sa|pitṛbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|pitṛbhyas}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇas}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛbhyas}} || mātāras || {{transl|sa|mātṝbhyām}} || {{transl|sa|mātṝbhyas}} |- | '''Genitive''' | pitur, pitras || pitraus || {{transl|sa|pitṝṇām}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇas}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇaus}} || {{transl|sa|dātṝṇām}} || mātāras || mātaraus || {{transl|sa|mātṝṇām}} |- | '''Locative''' | pitari || pitraus || {{transl|sa|pitṛṣu}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇi}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṇaus}} || {{transl|sa|dātṛṣu}} || mātārām || mātaraus || {{transl|sa|mātṝṣu}} |}
